questions.question:
Consider the following C code segment:

int a, b, c = 0;
void prtFun(void);
main()
{
    static int a = 1; /* Line 1 */
    prtFun();
    a += 1;
    prtFun();
    printf(" \n %d %d ", a, b);
}
void prtFun(void)
{
    static int a = 2; /* Line 2 */
    int b = 1;
    a -= 1;
    b += 1;
    printf(" \n %d %d ", a, b);
}

What output will be generated by the given code segment?

A.  3 1
    4 2
    1 1
B.  1 2
    0 2
    2 0
C.  6 2
    0 2
    2 0
D.  1 2
    2 2
    2 0

Suppose n and p are unsigned int variables in a C program. We wish to set p to ^nC_2, i.e., n*(n-1)/2. If n is large, which one of the following statements is most likely to set p correctly?

A. p = n * (n-1) / 2;
B. p = (n-1) / 2 * n;
C. p = n / 2 * (n-1);
D. p = (n * (n-1)) / 2;
